{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513845"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:15:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:15:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12238"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12238"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.06,0.83,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4760"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78429"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4760"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12238"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63791"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"164"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"1282"},{"type":"tags","id":"2273"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7564"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7774"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26770"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42717"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43992"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78429"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents with a two day history of recurrent headache. The headaches are one-sided, worse around the eye and occur in the form of attacks which last for 10-15 minutes. He has had about 10-20 attacks each day. They are associated with watery eyes and nose and are not triggered or exacerbated by anything. He had similar episodes of pain six months ago and they resolved spontaneously within two days. Since then he never had any episodes like the current one. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes, long-sightedness and a myocardial infarction two years ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis blood pressure is 132/78 mmHg, pulse 90/min and temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. On ophthalmologic examination the anterior chamber angle is visible, the retina is unremarkable and there is a pinpoint pupil. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Trigeminal neuralgia","Temporal arteritis","Cluster headaches","Migraine","Acute angle closure glaucoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with \u003Cstrong\u003Ecluster headaches\u003C/strong\u003E. Cluster headaches are characterised by repetitive attacks of headache that range between 10-30 per day for 2-3 consecutive  days followed by a symptom-free interval period that can be weeks, months or years. The headaches are severe and are characterised by autonomic symptoms like lacrimation, rhinorrhoea and Horner\u0027s syndrome (the cause of the pinpoint pupil). Pain in cluster headaches is not triggered by any activity like chewing, shaving, cold exposure, etc. The pain can last anywhere between 10-30 minutes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHeadache due to\u003Cstrong\u003E acute angle closure glaucoma\u003C/strong\u003E will be sudden with the presence of unilateral facial pain, decreased visual acuity and a mid-dilated, unreactive pupil. It is caused due to a narrow or closed anterior chamber angle which leads to the accumulation of fluid - a rise in intraocular pressure and headache symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMigraine\u003C/strong\u003E can present with symptoms like this but it is not associated with bouts of multiple attacks that last for 10-30 minutes. Instead, migraine lasts for anywhere between 24-48 hours associated with photophobia and phonophobia. It also usually has a trigger factor like chocolate, coffee, etc.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrigeminal neuralgia\u003C/strong\u003E presents with a severe, electric shock-like, facial pain that is episodic and lasts longer than the time duration mentioned in the scenario, it can last for days, but can be for minutes with triggering factors, and it is not associated with any autonomic symptoms. The distinguishing features of cluster headache from trigeminal neuralgia is that the pain is on the face and is is triggered by some factors like chewing, shaving, cold exposure or sometimes even air movement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETemporal arteritis\u003C/strong\u003E is a possible diagnosis. It presents with a unilateral headache in an older person. However, temporal arteritis will have a tender spot on the temple. It may include worsening vision, but it will not cause pupillary defects or autonomic symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cluster headaches are characterised by presence of 10-30 attacks of unilateral headache per day that is associated with autonomic symptoms.","Horner\u0027s syndrome, which includes ptosis, miosis, and anhidrosis, can be associated with cluster headaches."],"references":["Ljubisavljevic S, Zidverc Trajkovic J. Cluster headache: pathophysiology, diagnosis and treatment. J Neurol. 2019 May;266(5):1059-1066. doi: 10.1007/s00415-018-9007-4. Epub 2018 Aug 17. PMID: 30120560. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30120560/","Malu OO, Bailey J, Hawks MK. Cluster Headache: Rapid Evidence Review. Am Fam Physician. 2022 Jan 1;105(1):24-32. PMID: 35029932. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35029932/","Kandel SA, Mandiga P. Cluster Headache. [Updated 2023 Jul 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK544241/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63791"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12238"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63791"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T18:32:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T18:33:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4760"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78429"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCou